is, it's a way to speak to the web service,

00:36:16.599 --> 00:36:21.079
make it even simpler, it's the "X" in AJAX.

00:36:21.079 --> 00:36:27.610
Basically it's very simple, it's
client service, request, response.

00:36:27.610 --> 00:36:30.519
And the request or response is XML
which makes it very parsable.

00:36:30.519 --> 00:36:34.480
When you have something that this easy,
everybody wants to create a library for it.

00:36:34.480 --> 00:36:37.300
Everyone wants to do the easy work, right?

00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:40.150
So we have lots of libraries for doing XML-RPC.

00:36:40.150 --> 00:36:42.389
In Cocoa, there's web sevices core.

00:36:42.389 --> 00:36:47.679
AppleWcript has lots of libraries
for doing XML-RPC JavaScript.

00:36:47.679 --> 00:36:49.279
There's Dojo prototype.

00:36:49.280 --> 00:36:51.620
Lots of different ways of doing it.

00:36:51.619 --> 00:36:53.219
Python, Perl, .Net.

00:36:53.219 --> 00:36:57.009
You name it, it's probably got an XML-RPC library.

00:36:57.010 --> 00:37:01.410
And again it is what our web client
uses to talk to the wiki server.

00:37:01.409 --> 00:37:04.629
So all of the fancy...

00:37:04.630 --> 00:37:12.250
when Chris and John were changing meetings around, and
when things were showing up in the list automatically,

00:37:12.250 --> 00:37:15.920
that's all done using XML-RPC calls in the back end.

